===Etymology 1===
{{etyl|ang}} {{term|lufu}} (noun), {{term|lufian}} (verb), from {{proto|Germanic|lubo}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|leubʰ-}}. Akin to Old English {{term|leof|lēof|dear, beloved|lang=ang}}, {{term|liefan|līefan|to allow, approve of|lang=ang}}. More at [[lief]]

Noun: Love
lu-v

An act of which..

Patricia loves Ryan more than anyone or anything.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|lov|ing}}

# {{transitive}} To have a strong [[affection]] for.
#: ''I '''love''' my spouse''.
#: ''[[I love you]].''
# {{transitive}} To need, [[thrive]] on.
#: ''Mold '''loves''' moist, dark places''.
# {{transitive|colloquial}} To be strongly inclined towards something; an emphatic form of ''[[like]]''.
#: ''I '''love''' walking barefoot on wet grass.''
#: ''I'd '''love''' to join the team.''
# {{transitive}} To [[care]] deeply about.
#: "You shall '''love''' the Lord your God with your whole heart, and your whole mind, and your whole soul; you shall '''love''' your neighbor as yourself." (Matt. 22:37-38)
# {{transitive}} To [[lust]] for.
# {{transitive|euphemism}} To [[sex|have sex]] with, (perhaps from [[make love]].)
#: ''I wish I could '''love''' her all night long.''

